2) Card-Price-Tracker
a python program and website that aims to notify users when the price of a Magic the Gathering card falls below a certain amount.
3)During this increment we decided on deploying an existing project. Our team decided that to do so we needed to apply a different architectural framework. The design plans became a 3-layer system:
•	A React frontend handling all UI and user interaction
•	A Flask API handling data requests and business logic
•	A Neon cloud-hosted PostgreSQL database accessible to the whole team
The main accomplishment during this increment was documenting and understanding the architecture we had in mind, so we could prevent integration issues later on. The team identified that converting Flask into an API required defining an API contract a shared agreement on how the frontend and backend communicate before any code is written. The team also created a list of tasks and issues that need to be completed going into the next increment.
4) An issue was knowledge gap of the inherited code base and the decision to use React as that is what our frontend developer decided on using. This caused us to redesign our code to be focused on that decision which had effects like flask API. The idea of deploying this project also created an issue with the PostgreSQL so we decided to use neon for our cloud DB.
